00:02:04.940 --> 00:02:07.230
Thank you, Lily and
Charles, and now a few words

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:10.060
about Professor Chikashi Toyoshima.

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.990
Chikashi Toyoshima is a
distinguished biophysicist,

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:18.100
and professor at the Institute
of Molecular and Cellular

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:22.110
Bio-sciences at the
University of Tokyo in Japan.

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:25.780
He started his scientific career
as an electron microscopist

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:29.620
and worked on muscle
filaments and iron channels.

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:31.680
Drawing on his expertise in the fields

00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.500
of mathematics, physics, and biology,

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.260
Toyoshima has revealed
the atomic structures

00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:41.823
of biological samples that
could never be studied before.

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:45.520
Using x-ray crystallography,

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:48.590
he has determined the structure
of the calcium ATPase,

00:02:48.590 --> 00:02:51.930
commonly referred to as the calcium pump,

00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:54.453
and different phases of
the energy coupling cycle.

00:02:55.340 --> 00:02:58.170
Toyoshima's work on such
biological structures

00:02:58.170 --> 00:03:01.290
has revolutionized how
researchers are able

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:03.663
to study the structure of proteins.

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:07.050
Toyoshima is the author
of numerous articles

00:03:07.050 --> 00:03:08.750
in scholarly journals.

00:03:08.750 --> 00:03:13.320
His research on the calcium
ATPase, which began in 1989,

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:16.390
produced the first images of an ion pump

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:18.850
at work in atomic detail, and explained

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:21.500
why the structure has to be so.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.380
These images graced the cover of Nature,

00:03:24.380 --> 00:03:26.070
as well as served as an image

00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:27.963
for the journal's annual calendar.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:32.290
Chikashi Toyoshima was
born in Akita, Japan,

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:34.280
where at a young age, his studies sparked

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:36.610
an interest in the sciences.

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:40.640
He was accepted to the
University of Tokyo in 1973

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:42.080
in the physics department.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:45.640
And in 1978, chose to pursue biophysics,

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:50.640
receiving his Masters in 1980,
and his doctorate in 1983.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:52.940
After completing his degree,

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:54.908
Toyoshima served as a research associate

00:03:54.908 --> 00:03:59.870
at the University of
Tokyo from 1984 to 1986,

00:03:59.870 --> 00:04:02.800
as a postdoctoral Fellow
at Stanford University

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.890
from 1986 to 1988.

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:08.670
On a scientific staff the
Medical Research Counsel

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:11.330
Laboratory of Molecular Biology

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:15.460
at Cambridge from 1988 to 1989,

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:17.310
and as a research scientist

00:04:17.310 --> 00:04:22.310
at the Frontier Research
Project RIKEN in 1989.

00:04:22.411 --> 00:04:24.470
In 1994, he accepted a professorship

00:04:24.470 --> 00:04:26.140
at the University of Tokyo.

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:30.300
In 2005, Toyoshima was
elected as a foreign associate

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:32.500
to the National Academy of Sciences.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:36.160
And in 2006, he was
named a national lecturer

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:39.810
at the Biophysical Society's
51st Annual Meeting,

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:42.450
the Society's highest honor.

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:46.369
Please join me in welcoming
Professor Chikashi Toyoshima.

