00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:12.460
And I'd like to tell you how this protein

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:15.150
called calcium pump really works,

00:05:15.150 --> 00:05:18.203
and why structure has to be so.

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:22.070
But before going into details,

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:27.070
perhaps I have to introduce
for many nonspecialist

00:05:29.990 --> 00:05:31.770
why this protein is important,

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:34.390
and why the calcium is important.

00:05:34.390 --> 00:05:37.173
Perhaps many of you here knows that a cell

00:05:37.173 --> 00:05:39.920
is full of membrane compartments.

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:44.750
And this is just a cartoon,
but you see in the microcurve

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:48.393
and it's really full of
membrane compartments.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:54.650
Such biological membrane
consist of lipid bilayers.

00:05:54.650 --> 00:05:59.569
And lipid bilayer, it's of
course consist of phospholipids,

00:05:59.569 --> 00:06:02.260
and phospholipids has a polar head group

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:05.550
and hydrophobic tails called acid chains.

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:10.550
And they form this kind of membrane sheet.

00:06:11.510 --> 00:06:15.340
And so the driving force
is hydrophobic interaction.

00:06:15.340 --> 00:06:20.340
And what is good about this
is it self-assembles in water.

00:06:21.770 --> 00:06:25.820
And quite extensive one it can make.

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:29.770
And also, it dislike the hole is made,

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:32.000
so it's self-sealing as well.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.750
So it's kind of a super glue in a way.

00:06:34.750 --> 00:06:37.630
And it turns out to be
just really the super glue,

00:06:37.630 --> 00:06:42.630
and perhaps I'll show you
in the later of my talk.

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:45.550
And the property of this one

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:49.850
is that it is very impermeant to ions,

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:53.130
for example, sodium,
potassium, chloride is here.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:56.370
It's much more impermeant compared to

00:06:56.370 --> 00:06:58.313
water itself, pure water.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:04.890
And the result is you can
make a concentration gradient

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:10.430
for many ions important
for biological systems.

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:14.640
And the common one is
sodium, for example, sodium.

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:16.930
This is a case of muscle cells,

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:20.470
and I show you how the
muscle cell means that.

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:24.670
But here, the sodium
concentration outside of the cell

00:07:24.670 --> 00:07:27.800
is 110 millimolar, and the sodium inside

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:29.370
of the cell is 10 millimolar.

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:31.480
The potassium is opposite.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:36.480
So you see the tenfold or so
differences in concentration.

00:07:36.950 --> 00:07:39.800
But actually, the largest
concentration gradient

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:42.210
you see here is for calcium.

00:07:42.210 --> 00:07:47.210
It has more than 10,000
fold gradient here.

00:07:52.410 --> 00:07:57.410
And it's not actually rated,
this is divalent cations.

00:07:57.460 --> 00:07:59.520
You see the magnesium here.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:04.030
And magnesium is just same,
inside and outside of the cell.

00:08:04.030 --> 00:08:08.570
And what is important is this
ion concentration gradients

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:12.833
are used for many purposes
in biological processes.

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:18.300
They are certainly not in equilibrium.

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:22.820
And equilibrium means
it's, you are dead, right?

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:27.820
Why the calcium is so
important, explained here.

00:08:31.532 --> 00:08:35.410
Calcium is actually the
ion that's most widely used

00:08:35.410 --> 00:08:37.950
in regulation of cellular processes.

00:08:37.950 --> 00:08:40.530
And if you hear the word calcium,

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:44.460
perhaps you think of your bones or teeth.

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:48.420
And it's certainly true
because most of the calcium

00:08:48.420 --> 00:08:53.420
in your body is in your
(clears throat) bone and teeth.

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:59.193
One human body contains
about 1400 grams of calcium.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:04.677
But only 10 grams or
less, so it's less than 1%

00:09:05.860 --> 00:09:08.860
is used for regulation
of cellular processes.

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:12.820
So, it looks like very small amount,

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:16.230
but it has very important functions.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:21.230
And the human body has so
many calcium-binding proteins.

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:24.873
It's a good thing,

00:09:24.873 --> 00:09:29.480
I don't want to sort of
tell you about the diversity

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:33.970
of calcium seeing as there are
many excellent reviews here.

00:09:33.970 --> 00:09:36.590
So I just want to show
you just one example.

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:38.213
It's a muscle contraction.

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:45.150
You see here your arm muscle, it is,

00:09:45.150 --> 00:09:48.220
Muscle is a hierarchical structure.

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:51.400
So, it's actually a
bundle of muscle fibers.

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:53.440
It's called muscle cells.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:56.037
And muscle fiber itself is consist of

00:09:56.037 --> 00:09:58.623
mainly the bundle muscles.

00:09:58.623 --> 00:10:03.150
Thick and thin filaments
assembly called myofibril

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:05.529
surrounded by a secure system called

00:10:05.529 --> 00:10:09.143
sarcoplasmic reticulum
here, so you see here,

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:13.870
this bundle is called myofibril

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:18.360
it's actually consists of
thick and thin filaments

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:21.059
and it is surrounded by vesicular system,

00:10:21.059 --> 00:10:24.280
sarcoplasmic reticulum
and sarcoplasmic reticulum

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:26.263
is a store of the calcium.

00:10:27.330 --> 00:10:31.470
And we also see, so
this is a cross-section

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:35.970
of this one, so the sarcoplasmic
reticulum is this things,

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:38.900
and you see this is
actually a vesicular system,

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:43.170
and also the muscle system has the tubal,

00:10:43.170 --> 00:10:47.230
called transversal tube,
T-tubule here, right.

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:51.020
And when your brain sort of make order

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:54.360
with muscle to contract, then your muscle

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:58.288
then your motor neuron excites.

00:10:58.288 --> 00:11:00.260
The neuron excites, then

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:03.320
the action potential
is emitted and created

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:08.320
and goes down to the muscle
fiber along this nerve fiber.

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:17.663
But what happens here is like this.

00:11:20.350 --> 00:11:24.540
Your neuron excites first
at the sodium channel.

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:28.310
The channel for the
sodium ions sort of opens

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.673
and then the carbon potassium ions,

00:11:32.504 --> 00:11:35.700
potassium channels open
and turns out to make

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:37.520
this kind of action potential.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:42.360
So the initial stage is electrical signal

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:44.050
So the electrical signals come down

00:11:44.050 --> 00:11:46.680
to this synapse and synaptic end

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:50.190
then here voltage dependent,

00:11:50.190 --> 00:11:53.640
so-called voltage dependent
calcium channels exist

00:11:55.600 --> 00:11:59.150
and make a fusion of this
kind of vesicle also.

00:11:59.150 --> 00:12:02.410
This vesicles contain
the chemical substance

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:04.470
so-called acetylcholine.

00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:09.037
And acetylcholine is
emitted here like this,

00:12:09.037 --> 00:12:11.580
and so this is a chemical signal here.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:15.103
And chemical signal, so
the acetylcholine binds to

00:12:15.103 --> 00:12:20.103
its receptor on the other side
of these synaptic junctions.

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:26.010
And again, it's so that
acetylcholine receptor

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:30.580
is an ion channel, so
it's pass through the ions

00:12:30.580 --> 00:12:34.520
sodium ions now can enter this area

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:37.450
and forms the action potential again.

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:40.660
So the electric signal comes here,

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:45.520
then the channel opens, and
the receptor ion channel opens

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:49.520
and again it makes electrical signal.

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:53.946
So it's down to this part,
so it's called T-tubule,

00:12:53.946 --> 00:12:57.630
and there is a voltage-dependent
calcium channel,

00:12:57.630 --> 00:12:59.310
different one here.

00:12:59.310 --> 00:13:03.180
And it excites and it's opened

00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:06.620
the so-called calcium release
channel on the t-tubule.

00:13:06.620 --> 00:13:10.710
So the T-tubule is connected
to sarcoplasmic reticulum

00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:17.280
and so the calcium stored
in the sarco reticulum

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:19.650
released into muscle cells.

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:24.170
If the calcium is released it binds to

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:30.280
Troponin C and Troponin C's
a calcium binding protein

00:13:30.280 --> 00:13:35.280
and it moves along filaments
protein called tropomyosin.

00:13:36.740 --> 00:13:39.000
And tropomyosin sort of prohibits

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:40.850
the binding of myosin heads

00:13:40.850 --> 00:13:45.300
and when the calcium are
absent, but when its calcium

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:48.310
come to combine to this protein,

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:51.460
then this Tropomyosin moves and allows

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:55.498
this myosin head to move
productive interactions.

00:13:55.498 --> 00:14:00.498
Then the force is made, and
happens this kind of movement.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:03.203
So the key here is the calcium.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:09.713
As I told you that here
is the calcium channel,

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:15.820
the sodium ion channels, and
the calcium channel again,

00:14:16.530 --> 00:14:18.210
and the other calcium channel.

00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:19.500
So there are many kind of

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:24.443
different kind of ions
actually used for excitation.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:32.220
One thing I try to stress here is

00:14:32.220 --> 00:14:35.680
the channel follows
concentration gradient.

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:38.820
So it's a diffusion process.

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:43.820
And no energy is actually
required so it's very efficient.

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:48.190
More than 10 million ions per second

00:14:48.190 --> 00:14:50.700
can go through a second.

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:53.013
It's a very efficient system.

00:14:55.110 --> 00:14:59.080
We learned that calcium
is a very important ion,

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:03.993
but why is the calcium so useful?

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:07.703
Say why not magnesium?

00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:14.360
And the answer is that
actually our systems

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:18.940
our living system,
because has lots of water

00:15:18.940 --> 00:15:23.940
and water a really unusual substance

00:15:23.950 --> 00:15:27.340
and so let's think about
what kind of properties

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:30.250
are required for a good
ion for degradation.

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:35.250
So the good ion here means
that a good ions easily

00:15:35.830 --> 00:15:40.619
pass through and can invigorate
the biological processes.

00:15:40.619 --> 00:15:43.740
So, speed is certainly important,

00:15:43.740 --> 00:15:48.740
if you want to make the
processing and the degradation

00:15:49.370 --> 00:15:53.170
fast enough, of course the
ions have to pass through

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:55.830
the ion channels quite quickly.

00:15:55.830 --> 00:16:00.830
And if the ions bind to many proteins,

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:03.460
it does not help for degradation,

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:07.530
so it has to have a very
good specificity, right.

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:12.137
But also, if you don't need many ions,

00:16:12.137 --> 00:16:14.420
that will of course help.

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:17.410
Because just a small amount
of change is good enough

00:16:17.410 --> 00:16:21.530
for degrading your biological processes.

00:16:21.530 --> 00:16:24.880
Then, the next question, so
I can sort of think of these

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:28.794
three parameters, then
the next question asks

00:16:28.794 --> 00:16:33.690
in which physical property does
determine these parameters?

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:38.270
Size of the ion, or the charges of ions?

00:16:38.270 --> 00:16:40.323
Or something more exotic?

00:16:41.857 --> 00:16:46.857
Well the answer is both charges and size.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:53.905
So the size of cells,
of course we have a lot,

00:16:53.905 --> 00:16:58.905
all the substances immersed in water.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And water is, I mentioned
that is an unusual substance.

00:17:05.110 --> 00:17:08.724
Because it has a strong polarizability.

00:17:08.724 --> 00:17:13.620
Polarizability means as a whole,
this is a neutral molecule,

00:17:13.620 --> 00:17:17.410
it has a charge, it's a
partial charge on oxygen,

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:22.410
tends to be negative and hydrogen
tend to be a bit positive.

00:17:27.622 --> 00:17:31.733
When you look at the sodium
chloride, that's the salt,

00:17:31.733 --> 00:17:35.370
when you dissolve it in the water,

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:40.370
it's not just separated
like independent ions,

00:17:40.970 --> 00:17:43.680
it's actually surrounded
by water molecules,

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:47.360
and sodium ion has a positive charge so

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:52.360
the negative charge of
oxygen sort of attracted to,

00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:58.523
attracted and aligned water
molecules to like this way.

00:17:58.523 --> 00:18:02.187
And for the negative ions,
charges chloride ions,

